{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionEvent cameras are sensors that generate outputs (events) responding to optical changes in the scene's luminance [2].",
    "For each pixel, an event is only produced when a brightness change is detected, which enables high levels of sparsity and temporal resolution when compared to traditional frame-based cameras.",
    "Given its high temporal resolution, often at sub-millisecond scales, data from event cameras contain very rich temporal features capturing subtle movement patterns.However, when processing event data with modern neural networks, usually the events are pre-processed in ways that discard a large amount of temporal information.",
    "For example, oftentimes a spatial CNN is used to interface with event-based datasets, which requires the event data be \"col-lapsed\" or \"binned\" into images [7].",
    "In some sense, this defeats the purpose of using event cameras in the first place, where the goal is precisely to capture these temporal subtleties."
  ]
}